    {
      "step_id": "118715b2",
      "step_index": 3,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "## 2) SAR reasoning (why these features matter for hERG)\nhERG blockers commonly have:\n1) **A cationic center** to engage electrostatic interactions in the pore (often with residues such as **Tyr652/Phe656 region** via cation\u2013\u03c0 / electrostatics and positioning).\n2) **Hydrophobic/aromatic \u201cwings\u201d** that make strong **\u03c0\u2013\u03c0 and hydrophobic contacts** with aromatic residues lining the cavity.\n3) **Appropriate length and flexibility** to place the charged center and aromatics into the channel cavity simultaneously.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:58:49.222618+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "6a315fdf",
      "step_index": 4,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "This molecule matches that SAR strongly:\n- The **dicationic ring** increases the probability that at least one N is protonated and able to **anchor** in the channel via electrostatics/cation\u2013\u03c0.\n- The **large diaryl (difluorobiphenyl-like) group** provides a **highly hydrophobic, \u03c0-rich surface**\u2014often correlated with stronger hERG binding.\n- The **butyl linker** gives the conformational freedom to **fit the cavity** and align the aromatic system with the hydrophobic pocket while keeping the cationic center in the right region.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:58:49.222635+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "96f147b3",
      "step_index": 5,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "A possible mitigating factor is that **dicationic** molecules can have **reduced passive permeability**, which can sometimes reduce *cell-based* apparent hERG effects. But many hERG assays are done under conditions where access is still sufficient, and strong binders can still show blockade.",
      "tool_name": null,
